  <article id="about-article-52M4DD9F" class="about_pub-article">
    <h1>About</h1>
    Lennert da Silva and Parish examined how Norway and Brazil adapted global accountability standards in their national curriculum policies. They analyzed these policies using thematic analysis, a method that identifies patterns within data. Their study found that while both countries were influenced by international guidelines, they each tailored these standards to fit their unique national contexts. Norway created a cohesive policy where different aspects of accountability supported each other. In contrast, Brazil's policy showed contradictions due to conflicts among social groups. This research highlights how global educational standards are interpreted differently based on local circumstances, showing both similarities and differences in how countries approach education. Understanding these adaptations can help improve educational policies to better fit specific national needs.
  </article>
  <article id="keywords-article-52M4DD9F" class="keywords-article">

  <article id="abstract-article-52M4DD9F" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    This paper addressed in what ways national curriculum policy in Norway and Brazil adopted the global accountability logic of which OECD and other international organizations are proponents. It borrowed from an institutional logics perspective to explain the complexity found within the accountability logic across these two nation-states. The method used was thematic analysis of the national curriculum policy. The findings revealed that national curriculum policy is informed by the international context, but translated within national contexts. Norway elaborated the accountability logic to encompass multiple aspects of this logic that reinforced each other to create a cohesive policy. In Brazil, tensions between different social groups resulted in a curriculum policy with contradictory aspects of the accountability logic. The translations of the global accountability logic reflected the context-specific features of each country and illustrated both homogeneity and heterogeneity that still exists in different educational contexts.
  </article>
